column168: The driver stopped at a truck stop for a routine break aned vehicle check.  He noticed a leak coming from the trailer.  he returned to his truck and donned a respirator and protective clothing.  He then went to the trailer and checked inside.  he located a drum, midway of the trailer that had a hole in the side, about 1/4 of the way down.  He climbed out of the trailer and called the company.  A company representative called Clean Harbors Environmental Services.  Dan,, from Clean Harbors, contacted the driver and notified him someone would be responding to his location. The driver contained the material by placing "booms" around it and placed pads and Oil dry absorbant on the ground.  The cleanup crew arrived, found the faulty drum and plaved it into an overpack drum.
column169: The drum had a puncture hole in it.  Nothing was found in the trrailer that coulkd have caused the pouncture, so it must have happened before or during kloading.  Better care of the drums, preparation and inspection before using would be preferred.

column168: Consignment of 18 drums loaded and flown from international destination to Newark (EWR) Liberty Airport.  Drums handled several times prior to arriving at EWR where leak was discovered.  Preliminary investigation indicates that drum may have been dropped during buildup for initial flight resulting in small/minor depression at bottom seam.  This damage did not leak prior to air transport otherwise damage would have been noticed and remediated.    Leak resulted due to pressure differential while in flight.  Three ounces of liquid were observed and noted as leakage.    Clean-up was conducted in-house by Continental Airlines mechanics.
column169: Recommendation to international handling staff to note load drums exhibiting any evidence of damage regardless of size.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one leaking carton containing 0.47 liters was discovered leaking.  Approximately 0.47 liters of free product were released.  The release was due to improper packaging.  The dock area was evacuated and the Bradley Airport Fire Department was notified of the incident.  The Bradley Airport Fire Department evacuated the entire facility for safety reasons.  Environmental Services, Inc. of South Windsor, CT was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Environmental Services, Inc. performed the cleanup using absorbents.  The cleanup materials and wet carton with entire contents was placed into a 5-gallon plastic drum which was transported by Environmental Services, Inc. to their facility in South Windsor, CT for disposal.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been the result of a packaging failure, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: Driver entered location to make gasoline delivery, first time at site, was in the process of turning around in yard, which has an inclined driveway. Was almost done making turn when left side tank wheels came off of grond which resulted in tank unit laying over on its right side at a 90 degree angle. Tractor stayed upright, prduct started to spill from poppet vents on dome covers and vapor recovery pipe at top rear of tank. Driver immediately called the local Fire Department and Dispatch, applied absorbent pads and sausage booms, Fire Department applied more of the same and spread some foam, Highway Dept. built earthen dam to prevent product from reaching street and storm drains. Product flow estimated at 5-10 gallons per minute, carrier arrived with second unit and proceded to pump product off of overturn, removed as much product as possible, recovery crew than uprighted tanker which stopped all leakage from vessel. Tank was then off loaded on site into UST's, unit empty and towed from scene. Clean up crew on site to remediate.
column169: Driver should not have turned unit around, upon investigating this event it was apparent that there was ample room to complete the delivery as instructed on the station route card. Following directions would have averted this whole event, perhaps better training or reiterating the fact that the route card is a very valuable tool and must be adhered to.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by P&O Nedlloyd Lines, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Rotterdam Express from New York to Colombo, Sri Lanka.    The shipment was booked with one item of hazardous material: Resin Solution, Class 3, UN 1866.      The P&O advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from New York of additional hazardous material (Aerosols, Class 2, UN 1950, Limited Quantity) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional item.

column168: 4 metal drums were loaded on pallet(s), very heavy freight was loaded on top. The drums were not secured to the pallet allowing at least one drum to vibrate and walk off of the pallet. The bottom of the drum was then punctured by the pallet. A road driver had dropped this trailer at a relay yard when he noticed the material leaking from the bottom of the trailer. We contacted Haz-Mat One and had a team sent to clean up the spill and over pack the damaged drum.
column169: Proper blocking and bracing and not loading the heavy freight on top of the drums would have prevented this spill. The terminal that caused the spill will pay for the cost of the clean up and the cost of the damaged freight. This is part of our effort to prevent this type of error. ABF also conducts employee discussion reports and issues warning letters if warranted.

column168: PACKAGE CAME IN FROM TRAILER AND WAS WET ON BOTTOM. THIS LOOKED TO BE THR RESULT OF A HEAVY SKID BEING LOADED ON A LIGHTER SKID. FROM OUR MANIFEST EVIDENCE IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO ASCERTAIN WHOM IS RESPONSIBLE FOR INCIDENT. AT THIS TIME WE HAVE MOVED FREIGHT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE IN AN "AS IS" STATE. THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS WET AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE OF THE CANS OF PAINT HAD BEEN SLIGHTLY PUNCTURED CAUSING A SPILL WHICH WAS SOAKED INTO THE OUTER CARDBOARD PACKAGING.
column169: WE WILL BE LOOKING TO CORRECT THIS PROBLEM BY RETRAINING ANY EMPLOYEE THAT IS SEEN MISLOADING FREIGHT IN A WAY THAT IS DAMAGING TO THE PRODUCT. IN THIS CASE IT IS CLEARLY DUE TO HUMAN ERROR.

column58: Manway or Dome Cover; Manway or Dome Cover
column168: Driver arrived at Rhodia to pick up pre-loaded trailer.  When the driver arrived to pick up the trailer it was parked under the loading rack.  The driver hooked up to the trailer, but failed to go on top of teh loading rack to inspect trailer.  Once the driver left the plant he stopped and climbed on top of the trailer to insure all valves and domes were secure.  Because it was snowing, the driver did not feel it was safe to climb down the walkawy on top of the trailer.  The driver returned to his truck, and continued on I-85.  After mergin on I-26, the driver had to brake due to other traffic.  The driver noticed product coming out of the front dome of the trailer when he hit his brakes.  The driver pulled over to the side of of the road and noticed a small amount of product on the side of teh trailer.  He also noticed that the front dome wa not secure, and the product was leaking past the gasket and down the side of the trailer.  The driver then proceeded to the nearest exit and called dispatch.  Dispatch notified Rhodia, and they both proceeded to teh scene.  Upon arrival they bagan the clean up process, but ended up calling out Advanced Environmental Option, Inc. to survey the spill and condust the actual clean up.  After the product was cleaned from the ground, the trailer was brought to a tank wash to finish the final cleanup of the trailer.  The driver estimated loss of five gallons.
column169: Driver was sent to Superior Carriers Training and development Center in Kingsport TN, for further traning on proper pre-trip inspections.

Driver had completed offloading product from rail car into cargo tank, and was commencing to bleed down and disconnect the hoses when a minute leak started from the valve packing on the “A” side liquid valve.  Driver attempted to tighten down on valve packing and stop the leak.  Leak stopped when valve was closed and the pressure bled out from the lines and hoses.  Plug was replaced, the valve was marked, and the corporate office notified.  Fleet Manager evaluated “A” side valve the following day and was able to tighten the packing nut.  Valve no longer leaked.  Less than 5 pounds of material was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: At 1000 hr. 02/23/2006 boxcar PAL 701116 on TRRA rip track was found to be leaking product from inside of boxcar on left "A" end . Spill was contained and boxcar partially unloaded. Leak was found to be a polytote on the bottom tier. Polytotes were stacked on two levels one on top of the other and the bottom polytote had collapsed and become punctured by the top polytote. The leak appeared to take place immediatley after the boxcar was loaded on 02/14/2006. There was residual amount on the inside of the boxcar and truck frame and this was wiped down by absorbant pads. Two new polytotes were suppied by the shipper and the bottom polytote that was punctured and top polytote that was cruched were reloaded and car returned to service. The small amount estimated to be between 2 to 5 gallons of spillage on TRRA property was contained by our environmental contractor. The absorbant pads were contained in a 55 gallon drum about half full and considered non-hazardous waste and were removed off site by Illini Environmental Inc. to be dispsed of as per local, state and federal regulations.
column169: The metal supports on the polytotes need to be reinforced. There needs to be better Training on the part of the shippers employees in the loading process so as not to damage the polytotes.

column168: DRIVER WAS BELIEVED TO BE GOING TOO FAST AND TURNED OVER IN CURVE. WE WERE NOTIFIED BY A LION OIL PIPELINE EMPLOYEE THAT WAS WORKING IN THE AREA OF THE INCIDENT. HE INFORMED US OF THE CONDITION OF THE DRIVER AND THE FACT THAT THERE HAD BEEN A ROLLOVER WITH MINIMAL SPILLAGE OF THE PRODUCT WHICH WAS LIQUID ASPHALT. PERSONNEL FROM OUR FACILITY WENT TO THE LOCATION TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION. THE DRIVER HAD BEEN TRANSPORTED TO THE HOSPITAL, EXAMINED AND RELEASED. THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WERE AT THE SCENE. WE NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA DEPT OF POLLUTION CONTROL IMMEDIATELY, AND THEY CAME TO THE INCIDENT. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO PUMP THE PRODUCT OFF THE OVERTURNED TRAILER AND INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. THE WRECKER SERVICE UPRIGHTED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER AND TOWED TO OUR SHOP. SUMMITT ENVIRONMENTAL(CLEANUP COMPANY)CLEANED UP THE SITE AND ROLLED SPILLED ASPHALT AND DIRT INTO 55GAL DRUMS AND GRADED THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. CLEANUP COMPLETED.
column169: 1) REMINDED ALL DRIVERS AS TO THE DANGERS OF SPEEDING AS NOTED IN OUR COMPANY POLICY & PROCEEDURES MANUAL, SAFETY SECTION.  2)ENFORCING A BAN ON OUR TRUCKS TO BE TRAVELING HWY 15 SOUTH AND HWY 520, DUE TO NARROW AND CURVY ROAD CONDITIONS. SPECIFIED OTHER ROUTE TO BE USED.  3)SCHEDULED A MANDATORY SAFETY MEETING FOR ALL DRIVERS TO AGAIN GO OVER THE ABOVE MENTIONED ITEMS AND OTHER SAFETY ISSUES AND PROCEEDURES.

column168: UNDECLARED PACKAGE DISCOVERED IN UPS FACILITY.

At 11:00 am a leaking drum of waste paint thinner was found on a trailer while being off-loaded for transfer to another trailer at the Onyx Environmental Services 10-day transfer facility located in Pt. Washington, WI. Approximately one gallon of solvent leaked through the top bung of the drum and spilled onto the floor of the trailer. The trailer was equipped with a steel spill pan which prevented the material to be released to the environment. The container was placed into a salvage drum and the spilled solvent was cleaned up and shipped with the original container to the final TSDF for proper disposal. We suspect that there was water in the bottom of the solvent drum that froze while in temporary storage on the trailer. As the water froze it expanded and forced the solvent up through the bung.
column169: Onyx will instruct the customer to no longer fill the waste drums to the very top of the container.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS CARRYING 6000 GLNS. OF DIESEL FROM SHELL CHEMICAL REFINERY IN YABUCOA,PR. LEAST TO A GASOLINE SERVICE STATION IN AIBONITO,PR. (FROM EAST TO WEST). THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING FROM A MAJOR STREET #30, WHEN ANOTHER CAR PASS IN FRONT OF THE TANK CAR, PROVIDING THE DRIVER TO TURN TO THE LEFT SIDE OF THE STREET. THERE WAS A BIG HOLE ON THE STREET (12" HOLE). THE FRONT WHEEL GET INTO THE HOLE, AND THE DRIVER LOSSE THE CONTROL OF THE TANK CAR. WITH THE RESULT OF TANK CAR ROLLOVER AND A SPILLAGE OF 3000 GLNS OF GASOLINE. A FEW QUANTITIY OF THE GASOLINE SPILLAGE WENT THROUGH A SMALL RIVER, GURABO RIVER. LUCKILY WE CAN CONTROL THE SPILL ON THE RIVER USING A FLOATING BOOMS AND PAMPERS, AND OTHER ABSORENT MATERIALS. WE USED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER THE GASOLINE THAT WAS ON THE RIVER.
column169: DISCUSS WITH THE DRIVER ON HOW HE CAN PREVENT THIS ACCIDENT. IF HE COULD DO SOMETHING TO PREVENT IT. REVIEW THE TECHNIQUES OF THE DEFENSIVE DRIVING AND THE PROCEDURES TO AVOID OR PREVENT ACCIDENTS.

Package was discovered leaking on the main sort slide and response personel were notified. The responder, Kurt Burk, stated that liquid was present on the slide and the package carton was saturated with liquid. Responder determined the material was hazardous from the odor and from inner package labeling. The entire contents of the two bottles and the outer carton itself were processed In DMP. I was not able to inspect the outer package before it was processed. The responder stated that there was no packaging material or separators in the carton -just the two bottles, and no hazmat marking or labels of any kind on the package. The caps on the bottles were not secured in any way and closure was inadequate for transportaton.
column169: HazMat proceedures, including DOT regulations and UPS requirements, should be reviewed with this shipper. The importance of proper packaging of liquid hazmats should be explained. Customer’s service providers should be notified that shipper has submitted undeclared hazmats for transportation, and be on the alert for future problems.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, the Werner Enterprises driver came to a sudden stop, which caused the freight to shift inside the trailer.  The Werner Enterprises driver pulled into their UST yard to inspect the trailer, before proceeding to destination.  Upon opening trailer, a leak was discovered.  Hazchem Corporation of Addison, Illinois was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon inspection of the freight, it was determined that seven (7) 55-gallon drums had been damaged in transit.  Approximately 10 gallons of free product were released to the trailer floor.  Hazchem Corporation applied absorbent material to the free product, and overpacked the damaged drums.  Seven (7) 85-gallon overpack drums, containing the damaged containers, and one (1) 55-gallon recovery drum, which contained the spent absorbent material, were generated during the cleanup.  Disposal was coordinated per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to have occurred due to an abrupt stop, which caused the freight to shift inside the trailer, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Werner Enterprises will continue to reinforce safety guidelines in relation to blocking, bracing, and handling of freight.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  Upon arrival at the consignee location, Composites One LLC, a leak was discovered inside the trailer.  Apparently, it appeared that the freight had been damaged in transit, which caused a pinhole leak in the bottom of one (1) 55-gallon drum.  Less than one (1) gallon of free product was released inside the trailer.  Sunpro, Inc. was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Sunpro, Inc. applied absorbent material to the affected trailer floor, and overpacked the one (1) damaged drum into one (1) 95-gallon steel salvage drum.  One (1) 55-gallon recovery drum of spent absorbent material, and one (1) 95-gallon overpack drum were generated during the cleanup.  The remainder of the shipment was left on site pending disposition.  One (1) 55-gallon drum, and one (1) 95-gallon overpack drum were transported to Environmental Enterprises, Inc. for disposal per local, state, and federal regulations. column168: Product was shipped hot in a cargo tank.  Melting point is 139F.  When driver got to the consignee to make delivery, he was having problems getting the product to transfer.  There was frozen product in the elbow between the internal and external valve.  An attempt was made by the customer to heat the product in the elbow with hot water and steam.  That did not work.  The unloader had mentioned that sometimes when product freezes in the valve, they take the external valve off to get the hot water closer to the internal to melt any plug that might be in there.  When the unloader went to get his supervisor, the driver removed the external valve and used the steam and water to free the blockage.  At that time the internal valve indicator appeared to show the valve closed.  The plug of product became free and fell out of the elbow.  The internal valve failed to operate properly and the driver was unable to close it even with the emergency shut off valve. The driver was unable to replace the external valve because of the product flowing from the trailer. The product flowed on to blacktop, and into gravel and clay areas under tanks and pipes. Once on the ground, the product froze.  We contacted Hulcher Services to clean up the spill.
column169: The driver acted against company policy when he removed the external valve on a loaded cargo tank.  Schneider has taken steps to address this with the driver and is currently reviewing the procedure with all drivers.

column168: During switching operations in railyard, GATX 2848 and adjacent GATX 2854 were reported with small product releases from their 75 psi safety relief valves (SRV) after railcar movement was stopped in yard bowl track. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder found product trail and droplets on the top tank shell of GATX 2848 trailing from the SRV. Responder inspected the 75 psi SRV (last tested in 2001) finding no indication of mechanical malfunction. Responder concluded that product escaped via the SRV from hydraulic pressure surges. Responder cleaned spillage on GATX 2848 with a bleach solution. No ground impact was evident. Response concluded by 1330 hrs. CST, 2/02/06.  (Also see BNSF incident report 06-0202-0 1 A,B covering GATX 2854)

column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED GATX 26227 DRIPPING PRODUCT IN THE RAILYARD. BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER REPORTED FINDING PRODUCT DRIPS FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC). THE BOTTOM OPERATED VALVE HANDLE APPEARED IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND WAS PINNED AND SEALED. RESPONDER REPORTED THE HANDLE ON THE VALVE STEM WAS LOOSE. THE HANDLE WAS REMOVED WITHOUT DISTURBING THE SEAL AND RESPONDER FULLY CLOSED THE VALVE VIA THE VALVE STEM. HANDLE WAS REPLACED ON THE VALVE STEM AND TOOL TIGHTENED. THE BOC WAS ALSO TOOL TIGHTENED 1/4 TURN. THE BOC GASKET WAS NOT CHECKED. AFTER THIS SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED, NO FURTHER PRODUCT DRIPS EVIDENT. ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED. RESPONSE CONCLUDED BY 2140 HRS. CST, 2/09/06.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IF FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: While travelling on Interstate 75 at the Intersection of Highway 4 the tractor-tanker unit was involved in a roll-over.  Approximately 100 gallons of free liquid were released from the tanker and impacted the Miami River.  The Dayton Regional Hazardous Materials Team responded to assess the site.  Onyx Special Services of Huber Heights, Ohio responded to perform the cleanup.  Onyx Special Services used a vacuum truck to recover approximately 50 gallons of free standing liquid.  Onyx Special Services also applied absorbents to the affected asphalt surface as needed.  Four, 55-gallon drums of contaminated absorbents and one, vacuum truck containing approximately 50-gallons of free liquid were generated as a result of the cleanup.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL, DRIVER AND EMPLOYEE NOTICED A SMELL EMITTING FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  UPON CLOSER INSPECTION , A LIQUID AND FOAM WAS APPARENT UNDER THE REAR DOOR.  THE TRUCK WAS ABANDONED AND THE GENERAL MANAGER OF THE CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED.  THE PHOENIX FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE.  UPON ARRIVAL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SECURED THE SITE, EVACUATED THE IMMEDIATE AREA AND DIVERTED TRAFFIC AWAY FROM THE AREA. AFTER REVIEWING THE MANIFEST AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BILLS, THE PHOENIX HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM WAS DISPATCHED.  THE TEAM SECURED THE SITE AND FLUSHED THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WITH COPIOUS AMOUNTS OF WATER.  THE TRAILER WAS INSPECTED AND A LOOSE CAP WAS LOCATED ON THE TOTE.  IT WAS NOTED THAT LESS THAN A PINT OF MATERIAL HAD BEEN LOST.  THE SEAL ON THE CAP WAS CUT BY THE HAZMAT TEAM AND WAS TIGHTENED TO THE PROPER TORQUE SEALING THE TOTE FROM FURTHER RELEASE. THE FREIGHT WAS REFUSED BY THE CONSIGNEE AND AUTHORIZATION TO RETURN WAS GIVEN BY THE SHIPPER.  THE LOAD WAS INSPECTED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT  AND WAS APPROVED FOR CONTINUED MOVEMENT.  THE TOTE WAS TRANSFERRED BACK TO THE TERMINAL AND PLACED INTO THE HAZMAT BAY.  THE TOTE WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER ON 02/03/2006.

column168: 02/08/2006 1245 AFTER LOADING AT THE TULSA MAGELLAN WHILE EN ROUTE TO DESTINATION THE TRAILER 5TH WHEEL SLIDE LOST STABILITY. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHETHER HUMAN OR MECHANICAL ERROR CAUSED THIS. AS THE TRUCK/TRAILER DESCENDED A HILL THE TRAILER SLIDES FORWARD BREAKING THE SLIDE LOCKS AND SLIDE STOPS. ONCE THE SLIDE STOPS BROKE THE TRAILER CONTINUES FORWARD DAMAGING THE TRACTOR BLB AND RUPTURING THE 1ST COMPARTMENT PLUMBING. THIS TRAILER HAD 4" ALUMINUM PIPING WHICH SHELVED AT THE BOTTOM SIDE OF COMPARTMENT #1 (3000 GALLON). A TOTAL OF 2100 GALLONS WAS LOST. IT IS MY UNDERSTANDING THAT FUEL LEAKED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 HOUR WHILE EMERGENCY SERVICES WORKED TO PREVENT SPILLAGE/CONTAMINATION. SOONER EMERGENCY SERVICES DIKED WHAT SPILLAGE COULD BE PREVENTED FROM ENTERING THE CITY SEWER SYSTEM. THE SPILLAGE THAT DID REACH THE CITY SEWER WAS FLUSHED THROUGH WITH WATER COLLECTING AT OULET BEFORE ENTERING RIVER. TULSA FIRE DEPT APPLIED A FORM BLANKET AND VACUUMED UP THE CRUCIBLE SPILLAGE. MICRO BLAZE WAS INSERTED INTO SEWER SYSTEM TO BREAK DOWN HYDRO CARBONS.

column168: State trooper noticed a drip coming from cargo tank belly near a seam.  Driver put spill pad under the drip and the trooper contacted the local fire department.  I-10 was closed in both directions for about an hour. The trailer was diapered and the state police and fire department escorted the load to a tank wash facility in Creola AL where the product was transferred to another cargo tank. We called out HMHTTC to respond to the incident and stand-by while the load transfer was done. The spill on the side of the road was cleaned up by the fire department.
column169: The cargo tank was tested when it was empty and passed the internal and external test.  The shop did find that the insulation in the trailer was saturated which caused the drip.  Not sure where it came from.  It could have been rain water that seeped in there, tankwash water, a loose closure or product may have gotten in the insulation from loading.  All closures all the trailer did appear tight and secure when checked.

column168: Madison Freight Systems arrived at Cardinal Health Medical Products located at 1210 Waukegan Road - McGaw Park, IL to complete a delivery on 02/24/2006 @ 7:30 AM.  The trailer was positioned on an incline in the receiving dock. When the trailer door was opened it was discovered a 55 gallon drum of hazardous materials (Compound Cleaning contains phosphoric acid, 8, NA1760, PGIII) was leaking in the trailer.  Cardinal Health instructed the MFS Driver to pull out of the dock and SET Environmental was contacted to clean up the chemical spill which was still contained inside the trailer.  During the clean up process it was determined the chemical spill/leakage was caused by a puncture hole located near the bottom of the 55 gallon drum from another pallet which had an exposed nail on the end of the middle wooden stringer.  SET Environmental - 450 Sumac Road - Wheeling, IL 60090 - (847) 537-9221 performed the clean up and disposal of the hazardous material spill.
column169: A meeting was held with all the MFS Dock personnel regarding proper handling and loading procedures of hazardous materials.  Additional training is being provided to refresh the employees of the loading and securement requirements along with emphasizing the seriousness of handling and transporting hazardous materials.  We have contacted our Insurance Agent who assists Madison Freight Systems with training and educating the employees in many essential areas governing the regulations and personal health and safety. As a Company, we have a responsibility not only to our employees but also to the general public and will do everything possible to ensure an incident like this does not occur again in the future.

column168: FOUR DRUMS WERE ON 1 SKID AND WERE SECURED BY SHRINK WRAP.  DURING THE CORSE OF TRANSIT THE DRUMS SHIFTED ON THE PALLET BENDING THE LOAD BAR THAT WAS PROVIDING ADDITIONAL BRACING.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE STOP THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT ONE DRUM HAD A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM ONE OF THE DRUMS.  HE REMOVED THE BARRELL FROM THE SKID AND LAID IT DOWN FLAT TO TRY TO MINIMIZE THE SPILL.  HE ALSO REMOVED THE OTHER DRUMS FROM THE SKID.  IN THE PROCESS OF SECURING THE LEAKING DRUM THE DRIVER WAS USING A PALLET.  THAT PALLET HAD A NAIL THAT WAS STICKING OUT OF IT THAT HE WAS NOT AWARE OF AND UPON HIM WEDGING THE FIRST DRUM TO KEEP IT SECURE THE NAIL PUNCTURED A SECOND DRUM.  THIS ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS USED IMMEDIATELY FROM THE CUSTOMER TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT AT ABOUT 14:30 AT 15:45 THE PRODUCT HAD BEEN PLACED INTO 2 PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUMS THAT WERE PROVIDED BY A HAZARDOUS WASTE CLEAN UP VENDOR.

column168: THIS UNLABELED AND UNMARKED SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED TO CONTAIN A 4 INNER BOXES THAT WERE LABELED AND MARKED AS A DG SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND LYNETTE HURM OF THE SDF/FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND WAS TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT.  NONE OF THE INNER BOXES WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.

JIM DIGLABANI, MECHANICAL MANAGER, REPORTED TANKCAR TCDX 13266 WAS RELEASING PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND AT THE RATE OF ONE DRIP EVERY TEN SECONDS AND ADVISED THERE WAS A ONE FOOT PUDDLE UNDER THE TANKCAR IN THE RECEIVING AREA IN THE HINKLE YARD IN PORTLAND, OR.  MR. DIGIABANI STATED THERE WERE NO EXPOSURES AND THE PRODUCT HAD NOT LEAKED INTO ANY WATERWAYS.  THE RELEASE ORIGINATED FROM A METAL PLATE HELD BY FOUR BOLTS ON THE BOTTOM OF THE TANKCAR.  RICK SLOANE, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR. SLOANE WAS CONFERRED WITH MR. DIGIABANI AND WAS ISSUED INSTRUCTIONS TO ISOLATE THE RAILCAR IN ITS CURRENT LOCATION.  STATE REGULATORY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.    AT 02:04 PM, MGT. SLOANE REPORTED THE BOTTOM WASHOUT FLANGE WAS DETERIORATING AND HE WAS COORDINATED WITH THE SHIPPER TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT INTO TANKER TRUCKS TO MOVE IT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  MR. SLOANE STATED THE TANKCAR WAS BEING MOVED TO THE BEET SPURT IN THE RAILYARD FOR FURTHER ISOLATION.  AT 07:34 PM, SLOANE ADVISED THE RELEASE WAS A RESULT OF CONTAINER FAILURE.  MR. SLOANE STATED TRANSLOADING OF THE MATERIAL WOULD BEGIN ON 02/06/06.  MR. SLOANE FURTHER STATED THE DRIP HAD BEEN CONTAINED  AND THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL RELEASED WAS APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON.  FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.    ON 02/06/2006 AT 09:43 PM, MGR. SLOANE ADVISED THE TRANSFER HAD BEEN COMPLETED FORM TANKCAR TCDX 13266 INTO TANKCAR PORX 1639 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT AT 06:30 PM.
DURING INSPECTION, TANK CAR NATX 29969 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM OUTLET. CAP.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.

column168: RESIDUE SHIPMENT DODX 14346 WAS NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  CAR ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.    CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES RESPONDED AND TIGHTENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP STOPPING THE RELEASE.

THE DRIVER FAILED TO KEEP ENTIRE COMBINATION ON ROADWAY. PARTIALLY INTO A LEFT HAND CURVE THE TRUCK WAS ON THE FAR RIGHT HAND SHOULDER OF ROADWAY. IT WOULD APPEAR BY THE TIRE TRACKS THAT THE PUP TRAILER WAS THE ONLY UNIT THAT HAD LEFT THE ROAD WAY. THE PUP TRAILER BECAME UPSET UPON LEAVING THE ROADWAY. THE UNIT HAD TIPPED OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE ON THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. THE UNIT WAS THEN SLID DOWN ROAD BEHIND MAIN UNIT BEFORE COMING TO A REST STILL ON SHOULDER OF RIGHT SIDE OF ROAD. THE PUP TRAILER CONTAINED 3500 GALLONS OF DYED DIESEL FUEL. BECAUSE OF THE IMPACT WITH THE ROAD THE TANK SHELL ON THAT SIDE WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY. THREE MECHANICS FROM LOCAL GILLETTE, WY TERMINAL ARRIVED WITH FLOOR DRY AND SPILL KITS TO ABSORB FUEL AS WELL AS USING DIRT TO PREVENT FUEL FROM GOING FURTHER. THE ACCIDENT HAPPENED AT 9:20 AM. FUEL WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER AND THEN UPRIGHTED ABOUT NOON. THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 418 GALLONS OF FUEL LOST. THE REST WAS DELIVERED TO CUSTOMER AS ORDERED. THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS LATER REMOVED AND TAKEN TO AN APPROVED LANDFILL LOCATION. NEW TOP SOIL WAS HAULED IN AND ALSO NEW GRASS SEED WAS APPLIED ON SITE.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING BECAUSE OF THIS ACCIDENT IS BEING CONDUCTED.  THE PACKAGE DID WHAT IT WAS DESIGNED TO DO.  THE DOME LID HELD AND FIRE VALVE PROTECTION HELD AS WELL.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS HEADED TO PICKUP A CUSTOMER AND A VEHICLE CUT HIM OFF TO DO A U TURN. THE DRIVER APPLIED THE BRAKES TO KEEP FROM HITTING THE VEHICLE. HE DID HIT THE VEHICLE WITH MINOR DAMAGE TO BOTH VEHICLES. A COBB COUNTY POLICE OFFICER WAS IN THE AREA AND SAW THE INCIDENT HOWEVER HE LEFT THE SCENE WITHOUT REPORTING IT. THE OTHER VEHICLE THEN LEFT THE SCENE AND LEFT FALSE INFORMATION WITH THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO MOUNT PARAN CHURCH WHICH WAS ACROSS THE STREET FROM THE ACCIDNET. WHEN ONSITE THE DRIVER CHECKED THE LOAD AND NOTICED A LEAK FROM THE IBC. AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE SUPERVISOR AND A HAZAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. ALL STORM DRAINS WERE BLOCKED TO PREVENT CONTAMINATION. THE TRUCK WAS PARKED IN A CONSTRUCTION SITE AT THE CHURCH. THE SCENE WAS SECURED BY THE ATLANTA FIRE DEPARTMENT UNTIL THE GREENLEAF HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED. ONCE THE TEAM ARRIVED MEASURES WERE TAKEN TO MITIGATE ANY FURTHER CONTAMINATION. UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THE EPA THE MOUNT PARAN ROAD WAS CLOSED UNTIL THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP. THE MATERIAL WAS ABOUT A FOOT WIDE AND APPROXIMATELY 500 FEET IN LENGTH. OIL DRY AND LIME WERE UTILIZED TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE ROAD WAS SHUT DOWN FOR AROUND THREE HOURS AFTER WHICH OUR EFFORTS WERE CONCENTRATED ON THE TRUCK. TRANSFER OF THE REMAINING ACID WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER. THE TRUCK BED WAS THEN DECONTAMINATED WITH LIME AND OIL DRY. ONCE THE TRUCK WAS SECURE IT WAS MOVED SO THAT REMEDIATION OF THE SITE COULD BEGIN. THE SAME DECONTAMINATION PROCEDURE WAS UTILIZED FOR THE REMEDIATION AND SOME DIRT WITH GRAVEL WAS ALSO REMOVED. A ROLLOFF CONTAINER WAS UTILIZED FOR THE MATERIAL AND IT WAS THEN PROPERLY DISPOSED AFTER ANALYTICAL WAS COMPLETE.
column169: THE COMPANY IS NOW ADDING E TRACKING TO ALL THE TRAILERS AND BOX TRUCKS. THAT WAY A STRAP MAY BE USED TO BETTER SECURE ANY MATERIAL ON THE TRUCK OR TRAILER. IN ADDITION DRIVERS WILL BE TRAINED ON THIS INCIDENT AND DISCUSS HOW THINGS COULD HAVE BEEN DONE BETTER OR DIFFERENT.

column168: A HELEN CHEMICAL COMPANY DRIVER HAD BEEN INSTRUCTED TO DELIVER A 325 GALLON LOAD OF 52% P2O5 PHOSPHORIC ACID SOLUTION TO A DESTINATION AT THE INTERSECITON OF U.S. HIGHWAY 98 AND BROCKMAN ROAD, CALEXICO, CA 92231, APPROXIMATELY 25 MILES DISTANT FROM THE HELENA TERMINAL ON 101 W. CAREY ROAD, BRAWLEY, CA 92227.  tHE MATERIAL WAS CARRIED IN A SCHABEN INDUSTRIES 700 GALLON CAPACITY TRAILER-TANK.    THE DRIVER DEPARTED THE TERMINAL AT APPROXIMATELY 10:45 A.M., FEBRUARY 6, 2006. NO STOPS WERE MADE WHILE ENROUTE UNTIL THE DRIVER BECAME AWARE OF THE INCIDENT.    AT SOME POINT IN THE VICINITY OF SCHANIEL ROAD AND BROCKMAN ROAD, THE SAFETY PIN ON THE TRAILER JACKSTAND SLIPPED AND ALLOWED THE JACKSTAND TO LOWER TO ROAD.  THE JACKSTAND REBOUNDED FROM THE ROAD AND STRUCK AND PUNCTURED THE POLYETHYLENE TANK.  THE JACKSTAND BOUNCING ALERTED THE DRIVER WHO THEN PULLED THE CARGO TANK OFF THE ROAD AT THE EARLIEST POINT AND CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR FOR AID AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 A.M.  A SMALL LINE OF  PHOSPHORIC ACID WAS LEFT ON BROCKMAN ROAD OVER A DISTANCE OF 2.5 MILES.  IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 75 GALLONS OF SPILLED MATERIAL WAS DEPOSITED ON THE ROAD OVER THAT DISTANCE AND THE REMAINDER OF THE MATERIAL FORMED A POOL AT THE POINT WHERE THE DRIVER PULLED ASIDE.    HELENA PERSONNEL TRAVELED TO THE SCENE AND BEGAN COVERING THE SPILLED MATERIAL WITH LOCAL SOIL  THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL WAS ALERTED BY HELENA AND DISPATCHED A UNIT TO THE SCENE.  THE CHP OFFICER ORDERED KUBLER AND BROCKMAN ROADS CLOSED UNTIL THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED.  THE CLOSURE LASTED APPROXIMATELY FOUR HOURS FOR KUBLER ROAD AND ONE HOUR FOR BROCKMAN ROAD.  SOIL USED TO ABSORB THE SPILL WAS COLLECTED IN A TRALER AND THE MATERIAL WAS ULTIMATELY APPLIED AS FERTILIZER.    THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO HELENA PERSONNEL OR OTHER PERSONS.  ECONOMIC DAMAGE IS ESTIMATED AT $1,700.00 INCLUDING DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER, THE TANK, LOST PRODUCT AND CLEANUP COST.
column169: TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT, DRIVERS HAVE BEEN GIVEN TRAINING ON THE SECUREMENT OF THE SAFETY PIN WHICH HOLDS THE TRAILER JACKSTAND IN THE RETRACTED POSITION.  THE TRAINING REVIEWS THE INCIDENT AND DESCRIBES THE ACTION NEEDED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE JACKSTAND.

column168: A VEHICLE OPERATED BY CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC WAS TRANSPORTING A SHIPMENT OF A REGULATED LEACHATE FOR DISPOSAL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE COMFORT STOP AT A TRUCK STOP LOCATED AT MM29 ON I-65 SOUTH IN INDIANAPOLIS, IN.  UPON STOPPING AND SECURING HIS VEHICLE, THE DRIVER NOTICED THE REAR VALVE OF THE TANK TRAILER WAS LEAKING.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ENGAGED THE VACUUM ON HIS TANK TRAILER TO STOP THE LEAK, PLACED A CONTAINMENT PAIL UNDER THE VALVE AND CONTAINED THE SPREAD OF THE ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT THAT ESCAPED FROM THE VALVE WITH THE APPLICATION OF A SUITABLE ABSORBANT.  THE DRIVER THEN INSPECTED THE LOCATION OF THE RELEASE AND NOTICED THAT SEVERAL BOLTS ON THE KNIFE VALVE ASSEMBLY WERE LOOSE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TOOL TIGHTENED THE BOLTS ON THE KNIFE GATE VALVE ASSEMBLY.  ONCE THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED AND SECURED, THE DRIVER NOTIFIED BOTH HIS HOME DISPATCHER AND THE MANAGER OF THE TRUCK STOP.  A RESPONSE CREW WAS IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE TEAM CONTAINERIZED ALL SPILL DEBRIS AND CLEANED THE SITE PRIOR TO RELEASING THE VEHICLE.  PLEASE NOTE THAT THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO BOTH THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE INDIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT.
column169: PRIOR TO DEPARTING FOR THIS TRIP, THE DRIVER COMPLETED A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION AND DID NOT IDENTIFY ANY ISSUES ASSOCIATED WITH THE TANK'S VALVES.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN REINSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THAT A THOROUGH INSPECTION OF ALL CLOSURE DEVICES IS PERFORMED AT THE BEGINNING AND END OF EACH TRIP IN ORDER TO IDENTIFY ANY CONDITIONS THAT COULD AFFECT THE INTERGRITY OF THE PACKAGE.

column168: Wednesday February 01, 2006 (11:55):   • Received 12 drums of”Corrosive Liquids, N.O.S. (Contains Potassium Hydroxide, 8, UN 1814, PG II) from Magnablend Incorporated in Texas   (supplier of Expeditors’ customer). There was no visible damage or leakage to the drums at this point. Signed off clean by warehouseman.   Wednesday February 01, 2006 (Approx. 13:00):   • Inspected the paperwork and realized the freight was incorrectly consigned   • Notified the customer (KB Technologies) of the situation and contacted the trucker (Saia Motor Freight) to setup for the re-delivery.   Wednesday February 01, 2006 (Approx. 16:30):   • Trucker (Saia Motor Freight) attempted the pickup. The cargo was loaded onto the trailer. As the driver was inspecting the goods,   he realized that there was some residue/leakage from 4 of the 12 drums. He then refused the cargo.   Thursday February 02, 2006 (Approx. 09:30):   • The customer (KB Technologies) authorized a local HAZMAT certified packaging company to re-pack the damaged drums.   • The customer (KB Technologies) provided instructions to return of the goods to the supplier (Magnablend Incorporated).   • Environmental Projects Group, Inc (E.P.G.) arrived at 12:30 to inspect and repackage the drums. (see report attached)   • The repackaging took place at approx. 13:30. The drums were brought outside. E.P.G. cleaned the top of the drums and properly tightened   the bungs. Each of the damaged drums was placed in 95-gallon overpacks to avoid any further leakage.   • The customer (KB Technologies) and the supplier (Magnablend) were notified that the re-packaging was complete and the shipment   was available to being retuned to the supplier (Magnablend) as requested.   Tuesday February 07, 2006 (Approx 16:00):   The trucker (Saia Motor Freight) arrived to pick up the shipment to be returned to the supplier (Magnablend).

column168: Intermodal container OOLU 342864 was ingated at the BNSF intermodal facility at 1951 hrs. CST, 2/14/06. On 2/15/06, this container was noticed leaking an unknown substance from the container’s rear doors while it was being moved from the parking lot area to the trackside ramp area. OOLU 342864 was immediately taken to the intermodal containment area for further investigation. BNSF contract responders placed plastic sheeting around OOLU 342864 to catch spillage prior to opening this container. Inside, responders found double stacked/layered BC’s (plastic innards surrounded by metal cages) with no layer separators used. One top layer IBC has shifted during non-rail transportation. The extended metal lower foot and the boftom area of the cage (used for forklift tine insertion and support) of this shifted IBC had fallen into the top unprotected portion of the IBC below it, causing partial crushing and a cut in the plastic innards. All IBC’s were removed from the container and wiped down with acid pads. The inside of OOLU 342864 was pressure washed. The rinse water was collected and placed inside a new IBC. Approximately 7 gallons of the released product impacted the ground soil and this impacted Soil was excavated and placed into poly overpacks for future disposal. The remaining product in the damaged IBC was transferred into a similar IBC. The damaged IBC was washed and rinsed and held for future disposal along with all other clean-up material. All non-damaged IBC’s were returned to OOLU 342864 appropriately blocked and braced for export. Response concluded at 1600 hrs. CST on 2/16/06.

column168: THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS THE DISCONNECTING OF THE TWO INCH CAMLOCK LOCATED AT THE END OF THE LOADING HOSE THAT WAS CONNECTED TO THE PIPE GOING DIRECTLY INTO THE RAILCAR.  THE CAM LOCK WAS BEING HELD CLOSED BY A VELCRO STRAP FASTENED AROUND IT.  THE STRAP HAD BEEN IN USE FOR SOME TIME AND WAS ENDING ITS LIFE EXPECTANCY.  WHEN THE TRANSPORT TRAILER NEARED THE END OF THE UNLOADING CYCLE, NITROGEN GAS (INSIDE THE TRANSPORT TRAILER) MIXED WITH THE ISOHEXANE & CAUSED THE HOSE TO JUMP OR VIBRATE.  THIS CAUSED THE VELCRO STRAP TO COME LOOSE AND THE CAM LOCK TO SEPARATE FROM THE LOADING PIPE.  THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS ABOUT FIVE MINUTES.  THE COMPANY VACUUM TRUCK SUCKED UP AS MUCH PRODUCT AS POSSIBLE AND THE REST EVAPORATED. NONE OF THE PRODUCT LEFT THE COMPANY'S PROPERTY AND NONE GOT IN A WATERWAY.
column169: ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THE LOADING OPERATIONS AT THE SALES RACK(SPILL SITE) HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO REMOVE FROM SERVICE AND DISPOSE OF ANY OF THE VELCRO STRAPS THAT SHOW THE FIRST SIGN OF WEAR OR DETERIORATION.  AS THE CAM LOCKS OR HOSES START TO WEAR OUT OR ARE ROUTINELY REPLACED, AUTOMATIC LOCKING STYLE CAM LOCK THAT CAN ONLY BE UNLOCKED BY PHYSICALLY MOVING THE LOCKING DEVICES ON BOTH SIDES OF THE CAMLOCK WILL BE PUT IN SERVICE AND THE VELCRO STRAPS WILL NO LONGER BE NEEDED.

column168: Based on witnesses to the incident, the tractor and trailer drifted out of the right travel lane and impacted the guard rail. Due to the impact, the tractor’s passenger side diesel fuel tank ruptured, and sparks from the impact ignited the diesel fuel. The ensuing fire caught the tractor on fire, which destroyed the unit. The cargo trailer containing 9000 gallons of gasoline did not rupture or ignite due to the fire. However, the trailer did receive structural and heat damage.    Due to the type of cargo, public safety official closed the freeway in the event of an explosion.  A private response company was hired to remediate any remaining diesel fuel from the road surface and transfer the cargo from the damaged tank into a second tanker provided by Flying J Transportation. Upon completion of the transfer operation, the freeway was reopened.
column169: At this time, the cause of the crash is undetermined. One witness to the incident stated that he saw the driver asleep at the wheel. However, due to the time of the incident, it would be hard to make such a determination. Due to this claim and other safety factors, Flying J Transportation has implemented the below detailed instructions.    Flying J Transportation has instructed all drivers to remain concentrated on the whereabouts of their vehicle during any type of movement. They are prohibited from using cellular phones, coffee thermos or any other type of object, which could cause a distraction in the cab. Drivers have been instructed to immediately exit any highway or road surface and into a safe location the event that they become drowsy or feel the need for sleep.

column168: GATX 42810 was involved in a derailment 02-04-06. This Residue tank car, last contained Sodium Hydroxide Solution, spilled less than 1 pint of material. The material leaked from a broken weld in the area where the bottom outlet is welded to the tank. CSX Transportation dispatched Specialized Professional Services (SPSI), Cary Cowden, (877-228-7774) to clean-up the spilled material. The tank car will be cleaned and purged on site, then cut up for salvage.   Chemtrec Number-02052006-001   Cause Code: T207 (Broken Rail)   ATARI: 5(4 + 5 +0) (2 +0) =90

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Gasket
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Human Error; Inadequate Preparation for Transportation
column168: DURING AN INBOUND INSPECTION AT SELKIRK YARD OF TRAIN Q42704, TANK CAR PLMX 37759, RESIDUE, UN1170, LAST CONTAINED ETHYL ALCOHOL, WAS FOUND TO HAVE A PRODUCT DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP, APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE CAR INSPECTOR NOTIFIED GENERAL CAR FOREMAN MATT CARSON, A HAZMAT SENTINEL, WHO INSPECTED AND FOUND THAT THE CAP WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT SEATED COMPLETELY.  MR. CARSON TIGHTENED THE CAP AND RE-SEATED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE UNDER GUIDANCE FROM THE HAZMAT CALL DUTY OFFICER, MC BETHGE.  A REPORT WAS FILED WITH CHEMTREE 02042006-078, REQUESTING CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE.  TANK CAR PLMX 37759 WAS STAGED FOR 6 HOURS AND RELEASED TO BE FORWARDED TO A SHOP FOR INSPECTION.
column169: TALKED WITH CAR LEASEE, CAR WILL BE GOING FOR INSPECTION OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE AND SECUREMENT PIN, BOTTOM AUXILARY CLOSURE CAP GASKET AND WILL CONTACT SHIPPER TO REVIEW THEIR TANK CAR SHIPPING PROCEDURES.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DSR GLASSBURN WAS STRIPPING OUT TRAILER 314-9101. HE WAS TAKING OFF A SKID OF PAINT (PRO 344124012) OFF OF A RACK AND FOUND THAT ONE CAN OF PAINT THINNER HAD BEEN PUNCTURED.  ANOTHER SHIPMENT ON THE RACK (PRO 344060485), AN AUTO DIFFERENTIAL, HAD FALLEN OVER IN TRANSIT AND HAD TORN OPEN A CARDBOARD BOX AND THE CAN INSIDE THE BOX.  THE CAN WAS PUNCTURED IN ITS SIDE.  THE HOLE WAS ABOUT THE SIZE OF A HALF-DOLLAR.  THE LEAKING CAN WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM IN THE HAZMAT OSD BAY.
column169: THE DRIVER WHO LOADED THE AUTO DIFFERENTIAL SHOULD HAVE PROPERLY SECURED IT IN PLACE.  THE DRIVER WHO LOADED THE SKID OF PAINT SHOULD HAVE PUT DUNNAGE AROUND IT TO PREVENT THE PUNCTURE.

THE MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED TO INSPECT THE GASKET, THEN PROPERLY SECURED USING A CRISSCROSS PATTERN TO TIGHTEN EACH BOLT/NUT. column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON FEBRARY 12TH, 2006, AT APPROXIMATELY 4:53 P.M. CST, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT THE MSC PREFINISHED METALS FACILITY IN ELK GROVE VILLAGE, ILLINOIS.  DRUING OFF-LOADING OPERATIONS BY FACILITY PERSONNEL A LEAKING DRUM WAS FOUND IN THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM WAS CARRYING PAINT RELATED MATERIAL (UN1263). THE LEAKING HAD MIGRATED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR, OUT A WEEP HOLE ONTO THE TIRE AND GROUND.  APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF THE PAINT RELATED MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS ISOLATED ON THE TRAILER.  AT APPROXIMATELY 6:08 P.M. CST, MR. CHUCK WHITE OF KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE THE CLEANUP OPERATIONS.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER CONTACTED HAZCHEM ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSESS THE DRUM AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER ADVISED MR. WHITE AS TO THE ESTIMATED TIME OF ARRIVAL OF THE RESPONSE CREW.  THE RESPONSE CREW FROM HAZCHEM ARRIVED ON-SITE AND MET WITH THE DRIVER AND FACILITY PERSONNEL.  THE RESPONSE CREW PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A 85-GALLON OVERPACK.  THE RESPONSE CREW USE ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO COLLECT THE FREESTANDING MATERIAL FROM THE TRAILER AND GROUND.  THE SPENT ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER STATED TO LEAVE 85-GALLON OVERPACK FOR THE CONSIGNEE TO ACCEPT.  THE RESPONSE CREW SECURE THE SITE AND TRANSPORTED THE 55-GALLON DRUM OF SPENT ABSORBENTS TO A HOLDING FACILITY PENDING PROFILIING AND DISPOSAL.  ON FEBRUARY 13TH, MS. GINGER CARTER OF KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES CONTACTED CES, AND STATED THAT THE CONSIGNEE DID NOT WANT THE OVERPACK DRUM.  CES ARRANGED FOR HAZCHEM TO GO BACK TO THE FACILITY AND COLLECT THE OVERPACK FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: I need to report a Hazmat Incident that took place this weekend (Saturday 2/11/06)    Our driver Oscar Camacho truck 526 trailer 5345 picked up a load at our customer Onyx Environmental on Thursday 2/9/06 this load had a stop off in Grand View, Idaho on Friday and a scheduled delivery into Onyx in Henderson, Co on Monday 2/13/2006. Our trip number 06-0338.     Saturday evening approximately 5PM the driver noticed a very strong odor coming from trailer as he was stopped in Rawlins, Wy. he initially couldn’t see any leaking but the odor was too strong for him to enter the trailer to determine the cause. He called the number on the Manifest to Onyx at the origin, he was told this wasn’t the correct number to call but they would have someone return his call (no one did) He next called me on our emergency pager, we talked about the problem and I instructed him to call the emergency response number listed on the manifest, he was put in touch with Sean at Onyx to discuss the situation and course of action they wanted us to pursue. Sean asked if he felt the truck could continue to their facility and the problem could be corrected there. Per our earlier conversation Oscar said he didn’t feel comfortable doing that. Sean (Onyx) then decided to call out a responder. They chose to use RM Katt out of Denver,Co. Upon entering the trailer and examining the containers it was determined that two of the large metal totes had been over filled by the generator (Intel Corp, Hillsboro, Or) which did not allow for expansion due to elevations changes, The manifest number was 05013, the waste was (acetone) Katt completed the clean up as best they could and vented all the totes in hopes for prevent more over-flow, but they couldn’t rule out that this might continue during the remainder of the trip (Rawlin’s to Henderson) The driver checked again in Cheyenne, there was a little suspect venting but after a discussion with Sean at Onyx it was decided the truck should proceed to Henderson and Sean would make the necessary arrangements if any follow-up was needed.    This morning Monday 5/13106 Oscar made the final delivery without any further incident.    Please forward this to Insurance Company who should assign it a claim number.    Thanks for your help.  Paul  cJ  2/13/2006

ON 02/27/2006 OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE OSU AIRPORT WITH APPROXIMATELY 8000 GALLONS OF JE-A FUEL.  THIS PRODUCT WAS TO DELIVRED INTO ODOT; ABOUT GROUND STORAGE TANK.  UNABLE TO PHYSICALLY STICK THESE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANKS TO VERIFY THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THEY ARE HOLDING, OUR DRIVERS RELY OF THE TANKS GAUGING SYSTEM AND DOT PERSONNEL TO CONFIRM THAT THE AST'S WILL HOLD THE PRODUCT.  ON THIS DATE, THERE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN A MALFUNCTION WITH THE AST'S GAUGING SYSTEM.  OUR DRIVER WAS GIVEN CONFIRMATION BY AN EMPLOYEE OF ODOT THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT AND WAS GIVEN THE ORDER TO BEGIN PUMPING THE PRODUCT FORM OUT TRAILER INTO THE AST.  DURING UNLOAIDNG, THE AST BEGAN TO OVERFILL AND PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM 2 VENTS ON THE AST.  IT IS ESTIMATED TAHT 350 GALLONS OF JET-A FUEL ESCAPED AND WAS CONTAINED IN THE DYKE AREA.   PRODUCTS WAS CLEANED UP AND NO FURTHER IMPACT IS EXPECTED.

THE TANK CAR VAPOR PRESSURE WAS SCRUBBED OFF AND THE SHIPPER, BP AMOCO, WAS NOTIFIED THAT THIS CAR WOULD REQUIRE HOME SHOP DISPOSITION AND AN FRA MOVEMENT APPROVAL. column168: On 2/17/06 at Pittsfield, Ma., Pittsfield Yard, PROX 43479, Load Ethanol, UN1170, the CSXT Yard crew found some wetness on the top of the tank car during switching. PROX 43479 was setout to a secure track. The conductor notified the W. Springfield Yardmaster, who initiated the TERP Plan and called the PCC. The CSXT HazMat Call Duty officer was notified and received information as to the release of product from PROX 43479 and the approximate amount. CHEMTREC was notified - Report 02172006-058 @1814 hours. The HazMat Call Duty Officer contacted a CSX Emergency Response Contractor, Op-Tech Environmental Service - Albany Office, for a response team to investigate, handle and cleanup any release of product and to secure PROX 43479. Op-Tech representative, Doug Mockler, responded and found 4 of 6 manway bolts less than tool tight. The manway gasket was checked and the manway was re-secured. PROX 43479 was staged for 24 hours, re-checked, no leakage was found and car was forwarded for disposition.  Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

column168: At l230 hrs on 2-16-06, Frank Lerch, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety was contacted by FRA Hazmat Inspector Roy Gonzales. He reported observing tank car UTLX 802791 leaking on the mainline at the intersection of Hempstead Hwy & Bengle; Houston, TX. On arrival, Mgr. Lerch noted car to be dripping at a rate of approximately 1 drop every 15 seconds from a temporary magnet patch which was applied to the car on 1-11-06. Car is a residue empty last containing Hydrochloric Acid, UN1789, and was moving to Chandler & Son Tank Car facility in Piantersville, TX. under FRA Movement Approval # 06010025; reference Dot 5800.1, report # 8106. Upon determining source of release, Mgr. Lerch secured a bucket under the car, and had it spotted in a nearby siding track for further handling. At approximately l43Ohrs, Mgr. Lerch spoke to shipper representative Bob Blake, Sr. Mgr. Distribution & Safety for Bayer Corp., advising him of the release and corrective actions to be taken. . On arrival of environmental contractors, the affected area was neutralized with a total loss of less than one gallon. The magnetic patch was then removed, and the bucket was further secured to contain product as it drained from the shell of the car. On 2-18-06, with the assistance of Regional Manager Chemical Transportation Safety Tim 0 Brien, a temporary patch was secured over the hole in the tank and the car was released for transportation to continue onto destination. At approximately 0800hrs on 2-25-06, Mgr. O Brien responded to the Englewood train yard car repair facility; Houston, TX. Car UTLX 802791 was reported to be off gassing through the applied patch. With the assistance of environmental contractors, the patch was removed, and approximately five gallons of residue product was drained into a bucket. A new patch was then reapplied, and the car was released for transportation without further incident. There were no drains, waterways affected, or reported injuries resulting from this release.
